在案件中，已被命令将现在失业的ROM分配现场的所有者订购，以支付210万美元的任天堂损失，并在案件中辩护。 2019年9月，任天堂在洛杉矶居民Matthew Storman提出了诉讼，在他的Romuniverse.com的运作中提出了一个突出的下载＆＃34;任天堂开关场景Roms＆＃34;和其他受版权保护的游戏文件。当时，任天堂表示，该网站已被＆＃34;在盗版的任天堂视频游戏和＃34中最受欢迎和臭名昭着的在线集线器中;对于＆＃34;十多年。＆＃34;
 Storman已承认，在2019年，该网站在收入中每年30,000美元到36,000美元的大部分。这包括出售＆＃34的直接收入;优质无限账户＆＃34;每年30美元，为用户提供更快的下载和限制。当风暴签署了9月2020日与任天堂达成的协议下关闭了网站，他说他从网站上派出了800美元。根据法院文件，Storman＆＃39;现在的收入主要来自＆＃34;失业和食品券。＆＃34;
 在解雇的动议中，Storman调用了＆＃34;安全港和＃34;数字千年版权法（DMCA）的保护，争论他只是一个用户共享文件的中立服务提供商。他还指出，他过去曾同意任天堂＆＃39; DMCA Takedown在过去的要求。
 然而，在沉积期间，Nintendo允许Storman承认他已经上传了Nintendo＆＃39;他自己上传了受版权保护的ROM文件，消除了A＆＃34的任何尝试;安全港和＃34;宣称。另一个企图基于＆＃34的Storman防御;第一个销售学说＆＃34;由于该网站分配副本而不是Storman＆＃39;个人财产，因此也未能去任何地方。
    Storman还通过未能尊重提供的命令和与他的网站管理员和＃34进行通信来激怒任天堂和法院;和＃34;数据显示每个盗版视频游戏已下载了多少次。＆＃34; 2020年9月，Storman表示，数据不再可用，导致任天堂指控他＆＃34;摧毁它。＆＃34;
  虽然任天堂最初声称Romuniverse负责＆＃34;数十万＆＃34;在受版权保护的下载中，基于网站截图收集的证据，该数字降低到50,000。任天堂认为，每张下载价格在20美元到60美元之间（卖出的新游戏的平均成本），因此它在收入1美元至300万美元之间。在为任天堂提供总结判决时（如Torrent Freak），法官建议这是一个明确的侵权案，其中一个＆＃34;原告拥有受版权保护的作品和被告复制的物质事实没有真正的物质问题作品。＆＃34;当任天堂寻求441万美元的版权损失 - 或者每49场比赛为90,000美元 - 法官将金额降至1.715万美元（每项工作35,000美元）。该金额应该足够＆＃34;赔偿原告的收入和阻止被失业者的损失和阻止被告人已经关闭了网站，而＃34;法官写道。
 法官还授予Romuniverse的额外400,000美元＆＃39;使用Nintendo＆＃39;商标盒艺术，从大规模1120万美元的询问。但Storman避免了＆＃34的永久禁令;未来侵权，＆＃34;与法官表明没有＆＃34;无法弥补的伤害＆＃34;鉴于货币损害赔偿以及该网站已经过时的事实。 
在预期荒谬的评论中：这种判决的目的不是从福利的某人获得210万美元（显然）。 任天堂不会收回一分钱，而马特兰先生不会支付一分钱 - 他＆＃39; s＆＃39; s被称为＆＃34;判断＆＃34; 这样的判断的目的是秉承任天堂的版权和知识产权，并使任天堂更容易在将来取消类似的网站。

note_en:
The now-unemployed owner of a shuttered ROM distribution site has been ordered to pay $2.1 million in damages to Nintendo after trying and failing to defend himself in the case. In September 2019, Nintendo filed a lawsuit against Los Angeles resident Matthew Storman over his operation of RomUniverse.com, which  offered prominent downloads of &#34;Nintendo Switch Scene Roms&#34; and other copyrighted game files. At the time, Nintendo said that the site had been &#34;among the most visited and notorious online hubs for pirated Nintendo video games&#34; for &#34;over a decade.&#34;
 Storman has admitted that, in 2019, the site made up the bulk of his $30,000 to $36,000 a year in income. This included direct revenue from the sale of &#34;premium unlimited accounts&#34; for $30 per year that provided users with faster downloads and no limits. By the time Storman signed a September 2020 agreement with Nintendo to shut the site down, he said he was deriving $800 a month from the site. According to court documents, Storman&#39;s income is now derived primarily from &#34;unemployment and food stamps.&#34;
 In a motion for dismissal, Storman invoked the &#34;safe harbor&#34; protections of the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA), arguing that he was just a neutral service provider for users sharing files. He also pointed out that he had agreed to Nintendo&#39;s DMCA takedown requests in the past.
 During a deposition, though, Nintendo got Storman to admit that he had uploaded Nintendo&#39;s copyrighted ROM files himself, obliterating any attempts at a &#34;safe harbor&#34; claim. Another attempted Storman defense based on the &#34;first sale doctrine&#34; also failed to go anywhere, since the site was distributing copies rather than Storman&#39;s personal property.
    Storman also angered Nintendo and the court by failing to respect an order to provide &#34;communications with his website administrators&#34; and &#34;data showing how many times each of the pirated video games had been downloaded.&#34; In September 2020, Storman said that the data was no longer available, leading Nintendo to allege that he had &#34;destroyed it.&#34;
  While Nintendo originally claimed that RomUniverse was responsible for &#34;hundreds of thousands&#34; of copyrighted downloads, that number was lowered to 50,000 based on evidence gleaned from screenshots of the site. Nintendo argued that each download cost it between $20 and $60 (the average cost of new games it sells) and that it had therefore lost between $1 and $3 million in revenue. In  providing summary judgment for Nintendo (as  noted by Torrent Freak), the judge suggested that this was a clear case of infringement, one in which &#34;there is no genuine issue of material fact that Plaintiff owns the copyrighted works and Defendant copied the works.&#34; While Nintendo sought $4.41 million in copyright damages—or $90,000 each for 49 games—the judge lowered the amount to $1.715 million ($35,000 per work). That amount should be sufficient to &#34;compensate Plaintiff for its lost revenue and deter Defendant who is currently unemployed and has already shut down the website,&#34; the judge wrote.
 The judge also awarded an additional $400,000 for RomUniverse&#39;s use of Nintendo&#39;s trademarked box art, down from a massive $11.2 million ask. But Storman avoided a permanent injunction on &#34;future infringement,&#34; with the judge suggesting that there was no &#34;irreparable harm&#34; given the monetary damages and the fact that the site had already been shuttered.
  In anticipation of a stream of ridiculous comments:  The purpose of this judgment is not to get $2.1 million from someone on welfare (obviously). Nintendo is not going to recover a cent, and Mr. Storman is not going to pay a cent - he&#39;s what&#39;s known as &#34;judgment-proof&#34;.   The purpose of a judgment like this is to uphold Nintendo&#39;s copyright and intellectual property rights, and to make it easier for Nintendo to take down similar sites in the future.
